<p><b>Homework vs tests</b></p>

      <p>Note the following key differences between creating a homework vs a test/exam:</p>

      <ul>
        <li><u>If creating a <b>test</b></u>, you'll be prompted to 
          select what test exercises you want to add to the test.</li>
        <p>
        <li><p><u>If creating a <b>homework</b></u>, your 
          <%= link_to "Scheduler", help_learning_conditions_path, :target => '_blank' %>, found on 
          the Learning Conditions page, will control how many exercises will 
          be added to the assignment.</li>
        <p>        
      </ul>

  <p><b>Apply learning conditions</b></p>

  <p>Recall that a learning condition is a rule that lets you schedule certain actions automatically. For example, 
    you could create a feedback condition to automatically release feedback on the assignment due date. Once you 
    create this rule, you can apply it to an assignment by <%= link_to_help 'attach_feedback_label_to_exercises', 
            text="attaching its label", {:title => 'How to apply learning conditions', 
              :width => '700', :height => '700'} %>.</p>

  

  <p><b>Preview and release the assignment</b></p>
       
       <p>Whether a homework or test, you can set it up to be released automatically on the start date/time you indicate. But as a general 
        rule, <u>you should always preview the assignment <em>before</em> releasing it</u>. Preview will show you what exercises are in the assignment, 
        and will show you any labels attached to the exercises. By previewing before releasing, you can make sure a) your assignment contains 
        all desired exercises and b) the desired learning conditions will be applied.</p>